    <h2 class="section-heading reveal">Abstract</h2>

    <div class="prose reveal">
      <!-- TODO: Replace with your actual problem statement paragraph 1 -->
      <p>
        Agentic AI robots increasingly couple high-rate multimodal sensing with learned perception and 
        foundation-model reasoning, yet deployment failures often trace to a sensor-to-decision bottleneck, 
        not weak models: an autonomy stack can report low per-frame latency and high accuracy on processed frames,
         but these "good numbers" fail to pay off unless predictions are anchored to fresh evidence at decision time. 
         In the wild, high-throughput but low-value streams (redundancy/sparsity, amplified by vibration) saturate onboard
          pipelines and induce queueing, delaying informative frames and forcing the robot to act on stale inputs. 
          SenseGuard closes this gap by making robustness a decision-time freshness objective. It unifies (i) an online,
           vibration- and context-aware adaptive de-duplication/downsampling policy that prioritizes timely delivery of informative 
           evidence under tight compute, and (ii) an offline, model-centric trigger that detects sustained degradation 
           and commits compact before/during/after multimodal evidence capsules, concentrating retention on hard cases 
           to accelerate continual improvement. Across open-source benchmarks and a physical robotic vehicle, 
           SenseGuard raises camera mAP@50 by up to +20 points, cuts inference latency by 31%, and reduces 
           LiDAR trajectory error by 75%, dominating dedicated adaptive baselines on both accuracy and efficiency, 
           with gains scaling to 8–11% under the harshest deployment conditions where models struggle most.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

